    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p><code>string[]</code> doesn't exist, I guess you mean <code>String[]</code>.</p>\n\n<p>For converting a <code>Set&lt;Integer&gt;</code> to <code>int[]</code> you'd have to iterate over the set manually.</p>\n\n<p>Like this:</p>\n\n<pre><code>Set&lt;Integer&gt; set = ...;\n\nint[] arr = new int[set.size()];\n\nint index = 0;\n\nfor( Integer i : set ) {\n  arr[index++] = i; //note the autounboxing here\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Note that sets don't have any particular order, if the order is important, you'd need to use a  <code>SortedSet</code>.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 334630,
      "reputation" : 5419,
      "user_id" : 661196,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 79,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/AxOll.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "Cygnusx1",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/661196/cygnusx1"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1313766624,
    "creation_date" : 1313766624,
    "answer_id" : 7123625,
    "question_id" : 7123580,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>If you use Java 5+ Autoboxing should take care of this...!</p>\n\n<p>What error do you get?</p>\n\n<p>edit: ok i see..</p>\n\n<p>Like other said:</p>\n\n<p>loop on your Set and just put the Integer inside the int[], autoboxing should convert it.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 97818,
      "reputation" : 116642,
      "user_id" : 265143,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 72,
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/q3JFs.jpg?s=256",
      "display_name" : "P&#233;ter T&#246;r&#246;k",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/265143/p%c3%a9ter-t%c3%b6r%c3%b6k"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1313766693,
    "creation_date" : 1313766693,
    "answer_id" : 7123641,
    "question_id" : 7123580,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>I guess the problem is that <code>Set&lt;Integer&gt;.toArray</code> converts to <code>Integer[]</code>, rather than <code>int[]</code>. So you have no simple way: you need to iterate through the set manually and add its elements to the int array. Converting an individual <code>Integer</code> to <code>int</code> is handled by autoboxing in Java 5 and above.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 133781,
      "reputation" : 3265,
      "user_id" : 335423,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 85,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/23c6e6bcabe4bf306390f7cc5f6ea2c3?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "filip-fku",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/335423/filip-fku"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 1,
    "last_activity_date" : 1527911136,
    "last_edit_date" : 1527911136,
    "creation_date" : 1313766903,
    "answer_id" : 7123696,
    "question_id" : 7123580,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>This should work, assuming auto unboxing!</p>\n\n<pre><code>Set&lt;Integer&gt; myIntegers; // your set\nint[] ints = new int[myIntegers.size()];\nint index = 0;\nfor(Integer i : myIntegers){\n    ints[index++] = i;\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 69527,
      "reputation" : 40941,
      "user_id" : 202214,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9a1f2f162c0ad0ec95af710b34907fff?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "Kevin Bourrillion",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/202214/kevin-bourrillion"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 13,
    "last_activity_date" : 1313824436,
